,Recommended,253030,12127225,"Posted: 17 September, 2014",all,spartounet,Awesome game! The concept is simple and you dive into it really quickly.The level editor allows you to create cool things easily.I highly recommand it!
,Recommended,253030,11971721,"Posted: 3 September, 2014",all,Anti,"After way too many hours of this game, I think I can finally write a review that does the game justice.First off, you should watch both trailers so that you understand a little bit about how the game looks by watching someone play it.  They both sum up what things look like very well.  I'll write my review first from a mechanics aspect and end with an aesthetic aspectControls:The controls for race the sun are very simple and, I think, intuitive.  Arrow keys make you turn right and turn left; Space bar is jump.  They are remapable though I'm not sure I would ever want to.  Controllers are supported, but the game plays just fine with the arrow keys.  I'm pretty twitchy from playing shooters and RTS though.  You can tap the arrow key at varying speeds and get performance similar to a joystick or controller.  I've never found the controls to blame for any of my deaths after about the first 15 minutesLearning curve:Race the Sun introduces a leveled progression throughout this otherwise arcade style game.  Your first run is very simple: Dodge things, and try to hit the yellow speed boosts.  As you advance, power-ups like jumps, world portals, emergency portals (a get out of dying free card) and even portals that instantly warp you to the end of that level start to appear.  You level up in an interesting way: by completing challenges that the game poses for you, ranging from simple (like jumping 10 times) to complex, like only turning left for two regions (levels) in a run.  You have three at any time, and the simpler ones are often worth less, but makes it so that you can always progress.  By introducing these new features one at a time, you can get to grips with the new one instead of the game dropping a lot of confusing stuff on your head.Customization:Another consequence of the leveling system is that the game rewards you with mods for your flyer.  They do a variety of things from increasing the amount of jumps you can hold, to letting you grab power ups from farther away, to turning faster.  It's a nice way to tailor your craft to how you like to play. Additionally, you'll get the ability later on to choose multiple to equip.Procedural Content Generation:The levels in Race the Sun are procedurally generated.  Under normal circumstances, this would probably be infuriating, because every time you crashed you'd have to learn a new world (you'll crash often).  However, Race the Sun generates the same world for everyone, probably based on number sequence for each day to act as the seed for the generator.  There's no  downloads involved, and you can play instantly when you boot up the game or play offline anytime.  Since the levels are generated, you can also go as far right or left as you want.Graphics:Simple, yet good enough.  Shadows are dynamic based on the height of the sun, and actually imact the play of the game.  After all, your craft is solar powered.  Most things are simple hedron shapes, but it looks good enough that the graphics don't ever distract me.  Besides, since the sun is always in front of you, you usually only see the dark side of objects.  Occasionally you can blind yourself in the sunlight (it halos nicely when you're staring straight into it) obscuring things around you but is never bright enough to actually blind you.Gameplay:I think the game is fun as hell.  As you can figure from the youtube trailer, you move FAST.  You will miss things by next to nothing. You'll crash often trying to catch that one speed boost that you know you can't make and it will only be your fault.  I've never found myself blaming the game for a death.  The games are the perfect length to hop on and play one between doing other things.10/10: Perfect execution on what it set out to do.  Doesn't try to do too much.  Looks good, plays better."
